[0m[33;1m[1;3mcommit 66f424babfdc654b7ff5fb0765b15b49d0ae08cb
Author: Mathias Fussenegger <f.mathias@zignar.net>
Date:   Wed Feb 12 16:08:16 2025 +0100

    Encapsulate dropped cols skipping for SourceParser in lookupName function
    
    The `SourceParser` had a list of dropped columns and used this to check
    if a column was dropped whenever it encounters a new field in the
    source.
    
    This worked so far because:
    
    - Dropping columns is only allowed if there are OIDs
    - Dropped columns had a `_dropped_` name prefix in the metadata mapping
      because the name of a column was used as key. This allowed to
      disambiguate between a dropped column, and a re-added column.
    
    Concrete example:
    
          Initial state:
            Column: oid=1, name=x
          Drop x:
            Column: oid=1, name=_dropped_x
          Add x
            Column: oid=1, name=_dropped_x
            Column: oid=2, name=x
    
          sourceParser encounters oid=1 -> lookupName returns _dropped_x -> matches dropped columns
          sourceParser encounters oid=2 -> lookupName returns x -> doesn't match dropped columns
    
    In https://github.com/crate/crate/pull/17127 columns can be stored as
    `List<Reference>`, that means we no longer need to prefix columns with
    `_dropped_`, but as a side effect of that, we'd have:
    
          Initial state:
            Column: oid=1, name=x
          Drop x:
            Column: oid=1, name=x
          Add x
            Column: oid=1, name=x
            Column: oid=2, name=x
    
          sourceParser encounters oid=1 -> lookupName returns x -> matches dropped columns
          sourceParser encounters oid=2 -> lookupName returns x -> matches dropped columns again !
    
    To resolve this, this changes the lookup function to return `null` for
    dropped columns.

